# CBP Binding Ruling Request

Drafts a complete binding ruling request package for U.S. Customs and Border Protection.

## Prerequisites

1. Merchandise specs with composition, dimensions, function, and manufacturing process
2. Supply chain and transaction facts including parties, terms of sale, and related-party status
3. Prior entries, rulings, or CBP correspondence (if any)
4. Target legal issue: classification, valuation, origin/marking, or other customs treatment

## Output Structure / Process

Use this document outline and required fields.

### A. Required Inputs Table

| Category | Required Data | Notes |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Requester | Legal name, address, contact, signatory title | Standing under 19 CFR 177.1(c) [VERIFY] |
| Representative | Counsel/broker info, POA date/scope | If submitting via agent |
| Merchandise | Trade name, technical name, composition %, dimensions, function, use | Include samples/photos list |
| Manufacturing | Countries, steps, critical transformations | Identify origin impacts |
| Transaction | Incoterms, currency, payment terms, assists, royalties | Valuation impacts |
| Related Parties | Ownership/controls per 19 CFR 152.102(g) [VERIFY] | Provide relationship facts |
| Prior Imports | Entry numbers, ports, dates, classifications, outcomes | If any |
| Prior CBP | Ruling numbers, CF 28/29, protests | Attach copies |

### B. Document Sections (Required)

1. **Cover Letter / Header**
   - Addressee: appropriate CBP office (NCS or CEE)
   - Subject line: “Binding Ruling Request – [Merchandise]”
2. **Requester Identification and Standing**
   - Entity details and relationship to merchandise
   - If not importer of record, explain direct and substantial interest
3. **Merchandise Description**
   - Technical description, composition by % and material names
   - Manufacturing process, key steps, and functional characteristics
   - Photos, samples, drawings, standards/certifications
4. **Factual Background**
   - Supply chain narrative and parties
   - Terms of sale, pricing, assists, royalties, resale proceeds
   - Related-party pricing methodology (if applicable)
5. **Questions Presented**
   - One issue per question
   - Use specific HTSUS subheadings or valuation/origin framework
6. **Legal Analysis**
   - Statutory/regulatory framework
   - Apply GRI 1-6 for classification
   - HS Explanatory Notes support
   - CBP rulings (HQ, NY) and judicial precedents
   - Distinguish adverse authority
7. **Exhibits and Evidence Index**
   - Numbered exhibits with descriptions
8. **Certification and Signature**
   - Truthfulness certification and authority
9. **Confidentiality Request**
   - Identify BPI and request protection under 19 CFR 177.2(b)(7) [VERIFY]

### C. Question Templates

Classification:
“Whether the subject merchandise is properly classifiable under subheading ____ HTSUS, or alternatively under subheading ____ HTSUS.”

Valuation:
“Whether transaction value is acceptable under 19 USC 1401a(b) [VERIFY], and whether [royalties/assists/proceeds] must be added under 19 USC 1401a(b)(1)(D) [VERIFY].”

Origin/Marking:
“Whether the country of origin for marking under 19 CFR Part 102 [VERIFY] is ____ or ____ given the described processing.”

### D. Legal Analysis Checklist

- Identify controlling statute and regulation
- Apply GRI sequence for classification
- Cite HS Explanatory Notes for headings/subheadings
- Compare to HQ and NY rulings with factual parallels
- Address adverse rulings and distinctions
- Include CIT and CAFC precedents when relevant
- Verify all citations are current

### E. Evidence Index Template

| Exhibit | Description | Purpose |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Ex. 1 | Product spec sheet | Composition and function |
| Ex. 2 | Manufacturing flowchart | Origin analysis |
| Ex. 3 | Photos/samples | Visual characteristics |
| Ex. 4 | Invoices/POs/contracts | Valuation |
| Ex. 5 | Prior CBP rulings | Precedent |
| Ex. 6 | Lab reports/expert opinions | Technical support |

### F. Certification Block

“I certify that the information furnished in this request is true and complete to the best of my knowledge and belief, and that I am authorized to submit this request on behalf of the requester.”
Name:
